        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We can estimate precisely the band-7 water-line emission from the energetics of the Spitzer and Herschel spectra, by extension of the models mentioned in the Science Case. HOPS 87's parameters are scaled from IRAS4B (see Science Goal 2) by the relative brightness of their mid- and far-infrared water lines, and by our own CARMA 1.3 mm continuum observation. To estimate the water emission by the underlying disk, we scale the observations of the embedded disk of IRAS4B (JÃ¸rgensen &amp; van Dishoeck 2010) to the larger disk area inferred from the mid-infrared water spectrum of HOPS 87 (a factor of 2.5), assume the same velocity profile as IRAS4B, and consider a range of temperatures within a plane-parallel, Keplerian disk model in the escape-probability formalism. The results, shown in Figure 4, indicate that we can detect each component definitively with sensitivity ï³ = 30 mJy/beam in the H2O 5(1,5)-4(2,2) line, and 6 mJy/beam in the two lower-frequency lines, both in 0.3 MHz channels. We could smooth up to 1 MHz per channel to improve sensitivity. We are sure to detect either the E-D shock, or the outflow, or both. 

Our continuum estimate is  scaled directly from our own interferometric continuum observations at 230 GHz with CARMA, and the object's submillimeter SED.

We note that the systemic velocity of HOPS 87 is small -- +11.0 km/sec -- so the H2O 5(1,5)-4(2,2) line will always lie at the bottom of the strong telluric absorption line. Thus we would benefit tremendously from an allocation of very dry conditions, such as the 0.5 mm ppwv assumed in the calculations shown in Figure 4. However, both of the Band 7 normal-isotopologue water lines have observed from Mauna Kea, and possibly observed as masers (e.g. Menten et al. 1990); quantitative science can be done with them under arbitrary excitation conditions, and even if the 325 GHz transmission is well below 50%.

Besides the issue of atmospheric opacity, our observational requirements are relatively straightforwardly satisfied. HOPS 87 is quite compact. To minimize beam dilution of the disk and infall-flow regions, and partially to reveal their extent (~0.2 arcsec), we specify the 12-m array and 0.13 arcsec resolution. In this configuration we would resolve out structure larger than 2 arcsec, but this would affect none of the three components for which we search (see Figure 2).

We would be happy with the default correlator setup for our four target lines, with the proviso that their basebands come close to spanning a sideband, and thus we may be vulnerable to any band-edge artifacts which remain poorly characterized. We will study existing information on these issues before Phase 2. The current setup also exceeds modestly the 12 MB/s data-rate limit, which we would also try to solve in Phase 2; as described above, we could decrease the spectral resolution to achieve this goal. 

We note that Mann et al. have observed Band 7 continuum in a Class II object for which HOPS 87 lies within the primary beam. They did not observe water lines, though, so we do not consider the proposed observation to be a duplicate.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
