        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We can estimate precisely the band-7 water-line emission from the energetics of the Spitzer and Herschel spectra, by extension of the models mentioned in the Science Case. The relevant parameters of the 2.3 km/sec E-D shock claimed for IRAS4B are given by Watson et al. (2007). Those for its outflow shock, taken to be 25 km/sec, are in Herczeg et al. (2012). To estimate the water emission by the underlying disk, we use the H218O 3(1,3)-2(2,0), 203.4 GHz emission line observed in the embedded disk of IRAS4B (JÃ¸rgensen &amp; van Dishoeck 2010),  and consider a range of temperatures within a plane-parallel, Keplerian disk model in the escape-probability formalism. The results, shown in Figure 4, indicate that we can detect each component definitively with sensitivity ï³ = 70 mJy/beam in the H2O 5(1,5)-4(2,2) line, and 7 mJy/beam in the two lower-frequency lines, both in 0.3 MHz channels. We could smooth up to 1 MHz per channel to improve sensitivity. We are sure to detect either the E-D shock, or the outflow, or both.

Our continuum estimate is also scaled directly from that observed interferometrically at 203 GHz by JÃ¸rgensen &amp; van Dishoeck (2010), and the object's submillimeter SED.

We note that the systemic velocities of IRAS4B is small -- +7.0 km/sec  -- so the H2O 5(1,5)-4(2,2) line will always lie at the bottom of the strong telluric absorption line. This is exacerbated by the fact that IRAS4B is viewed by ALMA through 1.7 airmasses at transit. Thus we would benefit tremendously from an allocation of very dry conditions, such as the 0.5 mm ppwv assumed in the calculations shown in Figure 4. However, both Band 7 normal-isotopologue water lines have observed from Mauna Kea, and possibly observed as masers (e.g. Menten et al. 1990); quantitative science can be done with them under arbitrary excitation conditions, and even if the 325 GHz transmission is well below 50%.

Besides the issue of atmospheric opacity, our observational requirements are relatively straightforwardly satisfied. Like HOPS 87, IRAS4B is quite compact. To minimize beam dilution of the disk and infall-shock regions, and partially to reveal their extent (~0.2 arcsec), we specify the 12-m Array and 0.13 arcsec resolution. To minimize beam dilution of the disk and infall-flow regions, and partially to reveal their extent (~0.2 arcsec), we specify the 12-m array and 0.13 arcsec resolution. In this configuration we would resolve out structure larger than 2 arcsec. Thus all of the water-line and continuum emission from the E-D flow and disk will be captured. Some of the outflow water-line emission might be resolved out (see Figure 2), but not enough to prevent its detection and imaging at high S/N. Some of the envelope continuum emission may be resolved out as well, but its analysis is not part of this program. 

We would be happy with the default correlator setup for our four target lines, with the proviso that their basebands come close to spanning a sideband, and thus we may be vulnerable to any band-edge artifacts which remain poorly characterized. We will study existing information on these issues before Phase 2. The current setup also exceeds modestly the 12 MB/s data-rate limit, which we would also try to solve in Phase 2; as described above, we could decrease the spectral resolution to achieve this goal. 
</prj:justificationText>
